Paper summary\
-------------\
The paper proposes using a digital twin of the electricity market to simulate carbon taxes, and uses a genetic algorithm to optimize the electricity price and tax.\
\
Comments for author\
-------------------\
The paper has some critical pieces missing which make understanding the work tough.\
The multi objective problem isn't explicitly formulated, which makes it tough to understand. What are the constraints on the problem?\
The algorithm is explained in a general setting, instead of explaining its application to the problem at hand. How do the mating and selection steps apply to the price and carbon objectives?\
The ElecSim model is  at the core of the  simulation work, but is not explained in enough detail to make sense. Some questions I was left with- how do new generators join the market? How does the carbon tax incentivize the participation of renewable energy? How do loads react to the changed price?\
The modeling of generator's response to taxes seems simplistic and is not validated with real data. Further, there is no comparison with existing carbon tax formulations. Taxation is a notoriously complex subject with uncertain reactions by people, and that complex nature either needs to be incorporated, or it needs to be argued why simple linear models might work. Also, the response of gencos to the tax isn't adequately explained either.\
