Paper summary\
-------------\
In this paper, the authors used the NSGA II genetic algorithm to find optimal carbon tax policies while using the market agent-based model ElecSim. The authors briefly mentioned the rationale for preferring genetic algorithms over the grid and random searches. Authors claim that the use of a multi-objective optimization algorithm to minimize the average electricity price and the carbon density is the novel aspect of the paper. The benefit of using multi-objective optimization algorithm is that we can use them as per the situation. Evaluations based on ElecSim on limited scenarios indicate that their proposed approach can minimize electricity cost to below 10/MWh and carbon intensity to zero.\
\
Comments for author\
-------------------\
While I agree with the authors to some extent, there exists a significant scope of improvement in the study. Though the authors have nicely articulated the problem statement, at the same time, they have oversimplified the formulation by limiting the parameter set to carbon price every year. In addition to that, I am a little bit surprised by the fact that the authors didn't compare their approach with existing state-of-the-art policies. The literature survey is also not quite comprehensive. However, given the context and the scope of this study, I am okay with a weak accept.\
